<div class="divider fade"><hr></div>

<div class="sec fade">
  <p class="lead">Biology's biggest bottleneck is not ideas. It is the physical act of running experiments &mdash; nearly all of it still done by hand, one pipette at a time.</p>
  <p>A liquid handler can dispense across tens of thousands of wells overnight with sub-microliter precision, but it takes an automation engineer around <strong>40 hours</strong> to set one up for a given protocol. Most research protocols run a few dozen times and then change, so the setup cost never amortizes and the robots collect dust while researchers keep pipetting by hand.</p>
</div>

<div class="divider fade"><hr></div>

<div class="sec fade">
  <p>Baseplate is a centralized cloud lab with roots in San Francisco and Hyderabad. Researchers submit experiments through software, our robotic infrastructure runs them, and data comes back. When experiments from many groups flow through shared machines, every robot stays busy even if each customer only needs a handful of runs, and per-experiment pricing drops low enough that automation becomes the obvious choice over doing it by hand.</p>
  <p>That volume unlocks a real flywheel. High utilization lets you produce reagents in-house&mdash;enzymes, competent cells, media&mdash;which is where most of the cost actually lives. In centralized DNA assembly, biologics alone account for over half the per-experiment cost and drop <strong>10&times;</strong> when produced internally. Setup costs that run $80 per experiment when a protocol is used fifty times drop to pennies when batched across thousands of customers. Your costs start approaching raw chemicals and electricity, and a billion years of evolution made those remarkably cheap.</p>
  <p>The first cloud labs got this logic right but tried to be general purpose from day one, pushing all the logistics onto the customer. We start narrow and solve specific workflows end to end&mdash;plasmid prep, cloning, compound screening&mdash;where the customer sends a sample and gets data back with nothing in between, then expand from there.</p>
</div>

<div class="divider fade"><hr></div>

<div class="sec fade">
  <p>We are building out of San Francisco and Hyderabad because this is a problem that rewards density, volume, and the willingness to do things that don't look glamorous yet. If experiments get cheap enough and reliable enough, everything downstream changes&mdash;what gets validated, what gets funded, what eventually reaches a patient. We want to find out how far that goes.</p>
</div>

